@NODE "introduction" "SMBMounter - Introduction"

SMBMounter - Introduction

SMBMounter is a simple GUI which allows you to quickly and easily configure and control shares mounted on your Amiga system using SMBFS. SMBFS is a nice little tool which allows shared folders on your network to be seen by AmigaOS as a standard filesystem, thus allowing you to access it through the Workbench, shell, file requesters and so on, as if it were a drive connected to your Amiga. However, it's a command line tool and so can be a little tricky to use.

For quite some time now, I've had a folder full of scripts which I'd written so that I could just double-click them and they'd mount my shares, but editing them was a pain, as was adding new shares. I had tried a couple of different applications which should make it better, but some were unstable, some were very big and slow, and none seemed to suit. So I said I'd write my own!

SMBMounter runs as a commodity so it can be called up with a hotkey. It holds a list of saved shares and a list of currently active shares, and allows you to freely edit, mount and unmount any entries in the list. However, you also don't need it running constantly, so you can run it, mount your shares, and quit to save an extra few CPU cycles :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "disclaimer" "SMBMounter - Disclaimer"

SMBMounter - Disclaimer

Okay, you know the drill... While I have tried to ensure this software won't cause any harm to anyone's system, I can't guarantee it, and I can't be held responsible for any loss or damage caused by the use of this software. There are so many different computer configurations out there, and I only have a couple of combinations that I can test, so all I can say is, "It Works on My Machine" :)

@{b}Security@{ub}
Please be aware that, while login details are stored encrypted on your hard drive, they are still transmitted as plain text across the network, and are still visible while entering them!! See @{"Security" link "security"} for more information.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "operation" "SMBMounter - How It Works"

SMBMounter - How It Works

SMBMounter uses an existing SAMBA and SMBFS install, and works by simply generating the arguments required based on the user's settings, and passing them to SMBFS. Because of this, it needs a working SAMBA installation and SMBFS installed also. It runs as a commodity, enabling the user to call it up via a hotkey to quickly mount and unmount shares, saving a good bit of typing and shell/script work.

To browse the available servers, nmblookup is used to find the master browser. This master browser is then queried for a list of all other devices on the local network which advertise SMB sharing, and returns their hostnames.

When a specific server or hostname is selected, it can be queried for the list of shares using smbclient anonymously. If access is denied, it tries again with a guest login. If this fails, SMBMounter is unable to obtain a list of shares for that hostname. There may still be shares accessible on that server, but they're not publically advertised.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "requirements" "SMBMounter - Requirements"

SMBMounter Requirements

SMBMounter has some minimum requirements which you should really have sorted out before running the application...

 - SMBFS (http://sourceforge.net/projects/amiga-smbfs/files/)
 - AmigaOS 3.x or compatible
 - A working TCP/IP stack
 - A network...
 - A SAMBA installation is also required to enable searching for servers and shares on your network. Without it, SMBMounter will still work, but you'll have to enter the server and share details manually.

SMBMounter has mostly been tested on OS4.1, and has been reported to work on OS3.0-3.9 and MorphOS 2.7. However, some minor issues seem to exist in some cases on these platforms. I've tried to minimise these issues and most of the time it works but your mileage may vary. I've included notes in the guide in parts which might show issues.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "installation" "SMBMounter - Installation"

Installing SMBMounter

Installing SMBMounter is simple! Just copy the entire drawer to wherever you want it and run it from there. Config files are stored in the program's drawer. An example mount configuration file is included to give you an idea of how to configure a share, but it's pretty self-explanatory I think!

The first time you use SMBMounter, open the @{"Preferences window" Link "config"} and set the correct paths for Samba Bin and SMBFS. The defaults should work in most cases but every setup is different!

Upgrading

If you are upgrading from a previous version, you can simply overwrite the executable and the docs. SMBMounter will then use your existing preferences and mounts, to save you having to set it all up again. @{b}However,@{ub} if you are upgrading from version 0.1, any saved passwords will have to be re-entered, as the encryption now used for them will garble them when they're loaded.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "usage" "SMBMounter - Usage"

Using SMBMounter

SMBMounter can start hidden like most commodities by specifying the standard tooltype CX_POPUP=NO, however by default the main window will open when it is run.

Starting SMBMounter hidden in combination with the automount option of saved shares will allow shares to be mounted automatically and transparently when your computer starts and SMBMounter is in your WBStartup.

Starting SMBMounter from the shell with the argument "debug" will produce some debug output which might be useful to you, but mainly to me, in finding problems.

Pressing the Help key with the main window active will call up this AmigaGuide document.


More detail on the usage can be found by following the links below.

   @{" Main Window   " Link "mainwindow"}  The main SMBMounter window

   @{" Program Menus " Link "menus"}  The menus of the main SMBMounter window

   @{" Edit Window   " Link "edit"}  The Edit window

   @{" Configuration " Link "config"}  SMBMounter preferences and tooltypes

   @{" Mounting      " Link "mounting"}  Some information on the mounting of shares

@ENDNODE

@NODE "mainwindow" "SMBMounter - Main Window"

The SMBMounter Main Window

The main window is very simple, and shows saved mounts, active mounts and contains a quick way of mounting a share for a single use. Help (in the form of this guide) is available from the main window at any time by pressing the Help key.

The main window contains the following:

   @{b}- Saved Mounts listview@{ub}
This listview lists all the mount configurations currently stored by SMBMounter. Double-clicking on an entry will attempt to mount the share as a volume on Workbench, and if successful, the entry will appear in the Active Mounts listview on the right.

   @{b}- Active Mounts listview@{ub}
Any shares which have been mounted successfully by SMBMounter will be listed here. Double-clicking on an entry here will attempt to open the share's window in Workbench to browse just like any other drive. Please note that SMBMounter does not list any shares which it did not mount, so if you have other shares mounted by scripts or another application, they won't show up in this list.

   @{b}- New@{ub}
New creates a new entry in the Saved Mounts listview and opens the @{"Edit window" LINK "edit"} to allow you to configure it.

   @{b}- Edit / Remove / Mount buttons@{ub}
Each of these buttons carries out its operation on the highlighted entry in the Saved Mounts listview. Edit opens the @{"Edit window" LINK "edit"} to edit the selected share's details. Remove removes the share from the list. Mount attempts to mount the selected share, just like double-clicking it.

   @{b}- Unmount button@{ub}
This button attempts to unmount the selected entry in the Active Mounts by breaking the relevant SMBFS task. Be careful! Ensure that nothing else is using the mounted share as SMBMounter cannot tell if it is in use.

   @{b}- QuickMount text box@{ub}
The QuickMount text box is a handy gadget that lets you quickly type in a share's address and then tries to mount it when you press enter or click Go. Enter the address of the share as follows:

    //hostname/share

QuickMount will always ask you for a username and password for the share before it tries to mount it. If the share doesn't require a username or password, simple click "Connect" or press enter, and SMBMounter will try to connect without login details. If successful, QuickMount shares will be listed in the Active Mounts listview as usual, and can be opened and unmounted as usual. However they will not be added to the Saved Mounts list.

   @{b}- QuickMount ? Gadget@{ub}

The "?" gadget beside the QuickMount text box will search your local network for any devices advertising SMB sharing. Once these have been scanned, SMBMounter will present you with a list of servers found. Select a server by double-clicking it or highlighting it and clicking Select. A second list will then open, showing any available shared drives on that server. Again, select one by double-clicking it and the correct details will be entered in the QuickMount box for you! @{b}Note:@{ub} This function might not work under MorphOS, in which case you'll need to enter the necessary details by hand.

Clicking the close gadget of SMBMounter's main window will make it hide, much like most other commodities. You can make it appear again by using the hotkey defined in the icon's tooltypes (by default <ctrl alt s>), or by using the Exchange program. To quit SMBMounter, use the menu item or the "Remove" button in Exchange.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "menus" "SMBMounter - Program Menus"

SMBMounter Program Menus

The main window uses some menus for controlling SMBFS. Three main menus are provided - Project, Mount and Settings. The menu items function as follows:

   @{b}- Project->Save All Mounts@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga S)
Saves all mounts in the Saved Mounts list. Use this to save all the mounts you've edited since SMBMounter was started. If you try to quit SMBMounter with unsaved changes to your mounts, it will warn you and give you the option to save them at that stage.

   @{b}- Project->Hide@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga H)
Hides the SMBMounter window from view. Use the hotkey (default <ctrl alt s> or the Exchange program to show the window again.

   @{b}- Project->About...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga ?)
Shows an About requester containing version information.

   @{b}- Project->Unmount All...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga K)
Attempts to disconnect from all shares in the Active Mounts list. A requester will ask you to confirm first.

   @{b}- Project->Quit@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga Q)
Quits SMBMounter. If any mounts have been edited and aren't saved, you'll be given the option to save them when you quit. Also, you'll be warned if any mounts are active, though these will remain active when SMBMounter quits. This is because if you restart SMBMounter it will not be aware of the previously activated mounts.

   @{b}- Mount->Mount selected@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga M)
Attempts to mount the selected share in the Saved Mounts listview. Equivalent to Mount button.

   @{b}- Mount->Unmount selected...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga U)
Attempts to unmount the selected share in the Active Mounts listview. Equivalent to Unmount button. A warning requester will ask you to confirm unmounting the share - SMBMounter has no way of knowing if the share is currently in use!

   @{b}- Mount->Open selected drawer@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga O)
Tries to open the window on Workbench associated with the mounted volume selected in the Active Mounts listview. Equivalent to double-clicking the entry in Active Mounts. This requires ARexx to be active, and Workbench 3.5+ to work.

   @{b}- Mount->Create new mount...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga N)
Creates a new entry in the Saved Mounts listview and opens the @{"Edit window" LINK "edit"} to edit the new entry. Equivalent to the New button.

   @{b}- Mount->Edit mount...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga E)
Edits the selected entry in Saved Mounts in the @{"Edit window" LINK "edit"}. Equivalent to the Edit button.

   @{b}- Mount->Remove mount...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga R)
Removes the selected mount from the Saved Mounts list. Equivalent to the Remove button. Will not remove the mount from the Active Mounts list if it is already active.

   @{b}- Settings->Preferences...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga P)
Opens the @{"Preferences window" LINK "config"} for configuring SMBMounter.

   @{b}- Settings->Snapshot window@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga W)
Saves the current position and size of the SMBMounter main window

@ENDNODE
@NODE "edit" "SMBMounter - Edit Window"

SMBMounter - Edit Window

The Edit window is where you edit the details of a new or existing entry in the Saved Mounts listview. It's quite simple really, and gives you the following options:

   @{b}- Name@{ub}
The name this entry is given in the main window lists. If none is specified, a name will automatically be generated in the form of <service> on <hostname>.

   @{b}- Workgroup@{ub}
The workgroup in which the server you're connecting to is a member. Defaults to "WORKGROUP", or whatever you have set in the @{"Preferences window" LINK "config"}.

   @{b}- Hostname@{ub}
The name of the server hosting the share you want to connect to. Do not include the usual slashes - just the name itself. IP address is also acceptable here, again without slashes. Clicking the "?" gadget will search for and open a list of any servers on the local network which advertise SMB shares. Selecting an entry from this list will enter it in the Hostname text box. @{b}Note:@{ub} This function might not work under MorphOS, in which case you'll need to enter the necessary details by hand.

   @{b}- Service@{ub}
The name of the service you want to connect to. Again, do not include slashes here, just the name of the share. Clicking the "?" gadget beside this text box will search the hostname entered above for any shared drives it has available, and list them. Selecting one of these shares will enter it in the Service text box. If the server entered in Hostname doesn't exist or doesn't have any advertised shares, it will open a requester to tell you. @{b}Note:@{ub} This function might not work under MorphOS, in which case you'll need to enter the necessary details by hand.

   @{b}- Username@{ub}
The username required to connect to the share. Leave blank if none is required.

   @{b}- Password@{ub}
The password required to connect to the share. Leave blank if none is required. Note: passwords are stored encrypted, but will still be visible when you enter them! Editing an existing mount with a password will show dots instead of letters in the password box, but to change the password, delete all the dots and enter the new password.

   @{b}- Volume@{ub}
The volume name to mount the share as in AmigaDOS / Workbench. This name mustn't already exist on the system - if it does, simply change it here. If no volume name is specified, one will be suggested in the format <hostname>-<service>. Invalid characters will be replaced by an underscore.

   @{b}- Automount on Startup@{ub}
Checking this option will make SMBMounter attempt to mount the share as soon as it is started. This option disables the "Prompt for Login" option (see below), so that SMBMounter can be started hidden without windows popping up looking for login details. This option is especially useful for using SMBMounter from WBStartup, so you can easily have your shared drives mounted on startup.

   @{b}- Prompt for Login@{ub}
Enabling this checkbox will force SMBMounter to ask you for login details every time it tries to mount this share. This disables the username and password fields (as they're irrelevant), and the Automount on Startup option.

An example entry is included (Music on Buster) to show you a typical share setup, which you can delete or edit as required.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "config" "SMBMounter - Configuration"

Configuring SMBMounter

Apart from the mounts (which the user defines), SMBMounter is configured using the Settings->Preferences... menu item and through its icon tooltypes. Path settings in the Preferences window must be correct for SMBFS to work, as it depends on external programs to work.

The Preferences window contains the following options:

   @{b}- Samba Bin Path@{ub}
This is the path to SAMBA's bin directory. This directory should contain the files smbclient and nmblookup (which should be the case in any SAMBA installation). The default setting is SAMBA:bin, which should work in most cases. Click the "?" gadget beside the text box to call up a standard file requester to select the drawer with. SMBMounter will be unable to search for servers or shares on the network if this path is incorrect, though manually entering the details will still work.

   @{b}- SMBFS Path@{ub}
This is the full path to the SMBFS executable (and @{i}not@{ui} the drawer containing it). It defaults to SAMBA:smbfs, but may be different on your system.  Click the "?" gadget beside the text box to call up a standard file requester to select the SMBFS executable with. This setting is critical to SMBMounter working! SMBMounter will give errors when trying to mount shares if this path is incorrect!

   @{b}- FS Translation@{ub}
This option is used to control SMBFS's filesystem charset translation. When enabled, it will allow proper handling of foreign characters in paths and filenames between systems of different character sets. To work properly, you must specify a translation file. By default this is L:FileSystem_Trans/INTL.crossdos which should work in most cases, but if required, The "?" gadget can be used to call up a file requester to choose another translation file.

   @{b}- Default Workgroup@{ub}
This is the default Workgroup name to be used when creating new shares, and for mounting QuickMount shares.

   @{b}- Timeout@{ub}
This is how long in seconds SMBMounter waits for SMBFS and SAMBA to complete their tasks and return a result. It defaults to 10 seconds, which should work in most cases. Most of the time, the full 10 seconds isn't needed, and SMBMounter will only wait as long as it needs to. The acceptable range is 1-30 seconds. Bear in mind however, that timeouts less than around 7 seconds can cause some errors from SMBFS not to be caught as it can take up to 6 seconds to perform some tasks on my system. Some shares may take longer than 10 seconds to mount due to a slow network or computer. Increasing the timeout will stop SMBMounter reporting an error when the mount doesn't appear by the end of the timeout.

   @{b}- Use Screen Font@{ub}
This checkbox tells SMBMounter to either use the workbench screen's font (checked), or to use a user-defined font (unchecked), and defaults to checked. When unchecked, font selection gadgets to the right of the checkbox are enabled. These fields allow you to set the font face and size used in all the SMBMounter windows. Clicking the "?" button will call up the standard Amiga font requester to make choosing the font easier. It defaults to "DejaVu Sans.font" size 16 to match my OS4.1 setup, but will fall back to Topaz 8 (or whatever the basic system font is) if the selected font isn't available. @{b}Note:@{ub} the interface isn't properly font sensitive, so gadgets will not be resized to compensate. Therefore, size will be limited to between 6 and 20.

   @{b}- Sort Saved@{ub}
Use this cycle gadget to choose if and how you would like to have the entries sorted in the Saved Mounts list. The options are No, By Name or By Server. No means entries are left in whatever order they're found. By Name sorts the entries by the text displayed in the list for each entry (the text entered in the Name gadget in the Edit window). By Server sorts the entries by the hostname of the entries (the text entered in the Hostname gadget in the Edit window). Defaults to By Name.

   @{b}- Sort Active@{ub}
This cycle gadget performs the same function as the Sort Saved gadget detailed above, except it sets the sorting criteria for the Active Mounts list instead. Defaults to No sorting.

   @{b}- Suppress Automount errors when hidden@{ub}
This checkbox, when enabled, prevents Automount shares from opening requesters when SMBMounter is hidden. This can be useful for example if you run SMBMounter hidden on startup and your automatically mounted shares aren't available for any reason - the share still won't be mounted of course, but at least you don't have error messages popping up as soon as you start SMBMounter! Defaults to on. This option will not suppress the username/password option if an Automount share is set to ask for username and password.

   @{b}- Save / Use / Cancel@{ub}
Saves the settings, uses them until you restart SMBMounter or cancels any changes and closes the Preferences window.


Tooltypes

Tooltypes are used in the standard commodity way in the program's icon. The following specifically are used by SMBMounter:

   @{b}- CX_POPUP@{ub}
Defaults to YES. Controls whether the main window opens when SMBMounter is started. Set CX_POPUP=NO to start SMBMounter hidden, ideal if you start SMBMounter using WBStartup.
 
   @{b}- CX_POPKEY@{ub}
Defaults to ctrl alt s. Specifies the hotkey used to show the main window if it is hidden. Change this as required using the standard Amiga hotkey descriptions.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "mounting" "SMBMounter - Information on Mounting Shares"

Information on Mounting Shares with SMBSMounter

The shares that SMBMounter mounts, if successful, will show up as volumes to the Amiga, and so will appear like any other drive on your Workbench screen and in the shell and file requesters. SMBMounter verifies a share is successful by looking for the volume name becoming available, and only then will add the mounted share to the Active Mounts list. QuickMounts will be prompted for username and password details (which may be left blank and skipped by pressing Enter or clicking Connect). Saved mounts have the option of storing the password encryped with the mount definition, or of prompting the user for login details each time the mount attempts to connect.

SMBMounter will create a name and a volume name for QuickMounts in the same was it suggests a name when creating a new Saved Mount entry. If it happens that this name is already mounted (either as a share or another type of volume), QuickMount will fail and a normal Saved Mounts entry will be required with an alternative volume name. I'd imagine this would be unusual however unless the share is already mounted, as the volume name generated is <hostname>-<share>:

@ENDNODE
@NODE "security" "SMBMounter - Security"

SMBMounter - Security

As it stands, SMBFS isn't particularly secure, as it transmits passwords across the network as plain text. Unfortunately there's not a lot that can be done about this - it's just the way it is. SMBMounter can't help this situation, but starting with version 0.2 some security measures have been put in place.

 - Passwords are now stored in encrypted form with the details of each mount. This means however, that if you upgraded from v0.1, all your passwords are now scrambled and will have to be re-entered and saved again.

 - Passwords are not shown in the text fields when you edit the mount entry. @{b}However, they are still entered as plain text@{ub}, so make sure nobody's watching when you enter a password, either in the mount entry edit window, or in the password requester. Unfortunately, as SMBMounter uses GadTools (for compatibility with a minimal 3.0 install), there's no way to avoid this.

These measures are about as much as I can do without rewriting SMBMounter from the ground up, and possibly losing compatibility with basic 3.0 systems. I personally don't think it's a big deal anyway, since the casual observer clicking around your Amiga won't be able to get the passwords, and they're transmitted in plaintext anyway so a network sniffer would be able to get them from any SAMBA setup regardless.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "troubleshooting" "SMBMounter - Troubleshooting"

SMBMounter - Troubleshooting

The whole Samba and SMBFS thing is quite complicated, and Samba itself is well beyond the scope of this guide. Technically you don't need Samba working to use SMBFS, but it can help with troubleshooting to have local shares available.

SMBFS independently can also have issues. First off, make sure you have the latest version (1.74 at the time of writing). Read the documents and see if you can mount a problematic share by hand to see if the issue is with SMBFS, SMBMounter or the network itself.

SMBMounter itself has some shortcomings due to limitations with SMBFS. It tries its best to interpret error messages from SMBFS, but sometimes there simply isn't any feedback from SMBFS. These notes might help to pinpoint any issues you may have.

If your share shows up in the Active Mounts list, but doesn't appear on the Workbench and gives an "object is in use" message, this usually means an incorrect @{i}username@{ui} has been supplied for a Windows share. With a correct username, SMBMounter can detect if the incorrect password has been given (and will let you know), but SMBFS can mount a non-working volume instead of giving an error if the username is unknown.

Slow computers or network connections, or complicated shares with large numbers of files can mean it takes a long time to mount. When this happens, SMBMounter will wait until the timeout chosen in the preferences before giving an error, but when the mount eventually responts, it will still show up on Workbench as a volume. This volume can still be used of course, but SMBMounter won't have control over it. This situation can be helped by extending the timeout in the preferences.

Finally, I've heard that SMBFS has trouble connecting to Windows Vista and 7 shares, so that might be causing issues, in which case there's not really a lot that can be done I'm afraid. Some people have reported various hacks and registry tweaks which enabled Samba from the Windows side, but I haven't attempted this myself.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "future" "SMBMounter - Future"

SMBMounter - Future

SMBMounter works quite well as it is (on my machine anyway!), but I'm sure there are a few things which could be done to improve it in the future...

I'm also considering rewriting the GUI code for MUI instead of GadTools. This will enable various features such as a single multi-column list, proper font sensitivity, proper password gadgets, better looking under MorphOS, etc. Something to consider for version 2 anyway :)

Feel free to @{"contact me" Link "aboutme"} if you have any suggestions for future versions of SMBMounter!
   
@ENDNODE
@NODE "bugs" "SMBMounter - Bugs"

SMBMounter - Bugs

Known bugs:

 - Sometimes SMBFS causes a DSI error - this can normally be ignored in the Grim Reaper's "More..." window. I don't know what might be causing this, but the mount will still be successful if you ignore the error. This isn't a bug in SMBMounter itself, and it seems to be related to mounting the volume on Workbench. I have increased the stack assigned to SMBFS so this @{i}might@{ui} be resolved. Please let me know if it happens for you though!

 - Browsing for servers appears not to work for some people under MorphOS, but yet works fine for others. I haven't managed to sort this out completely, but I've done as much as I can without being able to reproduce it myself. It seems to be down to differences in the MorphOS version of SAMBA and certain network setups. In these cases, entering the information manually will work as expected.

If you think you've found a bug in SMBMounter, please @{"let me know!" Link "aboutme"} It would be a great help to include the debug output - this can be collected by running SMBMounter from the shell in debug mode and redirecting the output. For example:

Work:Tools/SMBMounter>  smbmounter debug >t:smbmounter-debug.log

Once the issue has occurred, the file in T: will contain more details about it which could help me fix the issue.

@ENDNODE
